meta {
  name: POST /api/chat/:patientId — turn 1: open the conversation (SSE)
  type: http
  seq: 1
}

post {
  url: {{baseUrl}}/api/chat/margaret-chen
  body: json
  auth: none
}

body:json {
  {
    "message": "What medication risks does this patient have?"
  }
}

script:post-response {
  // The done event carries the conversation_id; capture it so every later
  // request in this folder (follow-up, tool-chain turn, replay) continues
  // the SAME conversation.
  const raw = typeof res.getBody() === 'string' ? res.getBody() : JSON.stringify(res.getBody());
  const match = raw.match(/"conversation_id"\s*:\s*"([^"]+)"/);
  if (match) {
    bru.setVar('conversationId', match[1]);
  }
}

tests {
  test("stream opens with 200 and SSE content type", function() {
    expect(res.getStatus()).to.equal(200);
    expect(String(res.getHeader('content-type'))).to.contain('text/event-stream');
  });

  test("stream ends with a done event carrying verified citations and tools_used", function() {
    const raw = typeof res.getBody() === 'string' ? res.getBody() : JSON.stringify(res.getBody());
    expect(raw).to.contain('"type":"done"');
    expect(raw).to.contain('"citations"');
    expect(raw).to.contain('"unverified_count"');
    expect(raw).to.contain('"tools_used"');
  });
}

docs {
  # Turn 1 of the multi-turn workflow (spends guarded LLM budget)

  **What it proves:** grounded, citation-verified chat over the patient's
  stored record, streamed as **Server-Sent Events**. Bruno is not an SSE
  client — it shows the **raw stream** as the response body once the
  turn completes, which is exactly what you want for grading: every
  event is visible verbatim.

  This folder is a runnable **multi-turn agent workflow**: this request
  opens the conversation; `02` sends a follow-up that only makes sense
  with turn-1 context ("Is *that* above the threshold…"); `03` provokes
  the tool-use loop (watch `tool_use` events stream); `04` replays the
  whole persisted thread. Run the folder in seq order (a full `bru run`
  does this automatically).

  **The raw stream looks like:**

  ```
  data: {"type":"seed","conversation_id":"...","content":"I read the record during check-in (brief prepared ...)..."}

  data: {"type":"delta","text":"Margaret Chen is on"}

  data: {"type":"delta","text":" hydroxychloroquine ..."}

  data: {"type":"citation","citation":{"document_id":"doc-mc-001","cited_text":"...","verified":true,...}}

  data: {"type":"done","conversation_id":"...","citations":[...],"unverified_count":0,"tools_used":[]}
  ```

  - The `seed` event (M9) appears only on a NEW conversation for a patient
    whose prep has completed: the agent's **opening move** — a compact digest
    of the already-gated brief — persisted server-side as the conversation's
    first assistant message before your turn is processed. The transcript
    (see the replay in `04`) literally opens with it.

  - `delta` events carry incremental answer text (what the panel renders
    token-by-token).
  - `citation` events stream as each claim's supporting span arrives —
    already **re-verified verbatim server-side** against the stored
    document (native Citations API + our citation gate).
  - The terminal `done` event carries the `conversation_id`, the full
    citation list, `unverified_count` (spans that failed verbatim
    re-verification are *reported*, never rendered as provenance), and
    `tools_used` (empty when the attached record sufficed).
  - On a mid-stream failure you get `data: {"type":"error","error":"chat_failed"}`
    instead — internals are never leaked into the stream.

  **Guards answer as plain JSON before the stream opens**, so clients can
  branch on status codes: `400 {"error":"invalid_message","max_chars":2000}`
  (missing/empty/oversized message), `404 {"error":"patient_not_found"}`,
  `429 {"error":"llm_budget_exceeded","spent_usd":...,"budget_usd":...}`.

  **Request body:** `{"message": "...", "conversation_id": "...", "viewing_image_id": "..."}` —
  `conversation_id` is optional; omit it (as here) to start a new
  conversation, or pass a previous `done` event's id to continue one.
  `viewing_image_id` (IC3, also optional) names the scan the physician has
  open in the imaging workspace so "this scan" resolves: a valid id is
  folded into the model call as ephemeral UI context (the persisted
  transcript keeps your words verbatim — compare the replay in `04`); an
  unknown id is ignored and logged, never an error. Try it here with
  `"viewing_image_id": "img-mc-006"` and `"message": "Summarize this scan"`.

  **Post-response script:** captures `conversation_id` from the `done`
  event into the `conversationId` variable, so every following request in
  this folder targets this very conversation.
}
